Q2.8(4): I felt like there were some minor details perhaps missing, before the part about gluing the lid. Also the language "to make sure those little bits don't ever get out" sounded a little informal, infantile perhaps. Finally, I understood "maracas" but it's possible that many people wouldn't, since it is specific to a culture.
Q2.8(5): I'm not sure what 'chalk paint' is.
Q2.8(6): I think perhaps the word "the" before "paper" made me wonder if there were a specific paper the question was referring to (typically in English we would not use "the" if speaking generally, of any paper...)
Q2.8(7): The colander option didn't *not* make sense, but, given that the question was how to get water out of a coconut, technically I guess either answer could have been true - both described how to get the water out, although only one described how to catch it/keep it/contain it afterwards.  But even with a colander, you would have still gotten the water and performed the task in question. Also I think that perhaps not everyone has had experience getting water out of a coconut, so this might be based on culture (location, or, family culture/what groceries families buy and bring home).
Q2.8(8): "to a professional result" sounded a little strange to me; "for a professional result"?  Also, I'm not sure most people would put tape around their nails before painting, but the part about the Q-tip dipped in nail polish remover follows normally.  But I still chose that one because the other completely seemed wrong, since I've never seen anyone use "flesh colored" nail polish to paint over mistakes on the skin!
Q2.8(15): the only thing underspecified is whether or not the pen mentioned is possibly an erasable pen (if they even still make those). Otherwise, pencil would be the undisputed choice.
Q2.8(16): Between the two choices, pencil tip made the most sense.  However, most people would use a metal or wooden nail tool, as use of a pencil would be 1) gross and 2) would probably leave grey marks so it wouldn't actually achieve the effect of removing debris/cleaning, but rather would add more debris.
Q2.8(17): While a heating pad can work for aches and pains, I couldn't be sure if it would *always* alleviate stomach pain. Perhaps it depends on the reason for the stomach pain.  And I couldn't be sure about the modifier "quickly", either.
Q2.8(20): I can't remember how to make papier mâché, but I think the second one makes more sense.  The underspecified selection is because i think some information is missing: I think you must add water, or something else to turn the paper bits into a gooey liquid.
Q2.8(21): Certainly the colander option makes no sense because the cream would run through it, but, it's underspecified because why would you prepare plain heavy cream for baking (by itself)?
Q2.8(22): The fruits part makes sense, but it seems there is more to a balanced diet than only fruit.

Q19.8(8): I did not understand "straws."  I know what regular straws are, but, unless this is also the name of a specific part on a helicopter (perhaps it is - I'm not sure about parts names), then I would have instead checked "the question and/or answer did not make any sense."
Q19.8(14): I would want to know the type/size of cylinders.  If they were very large/heavy, I might have thought a different response would be more appropriate (using a machine, crane, etc. e.g. if they were huge, heavy cylinders).

Q19.8(17): I don't think you could really cover the opening with a pool noodle - although "opening" was underspecified. If taken at face value as the opening of the door, then, a noodle would be insufficiently small.
